## CODE GENERATION RULES (Freezed)

### Freezed Data Classes
```dart
import 'package:freezed_annotation/freezed_annotation.dart';

part 'user_model.freezed.dart';
part 'user_model.g.dart';

@freezed
class User with _$User {
  const factory User({
    required String id,
    required String email,
    String? displayName,
    @Default(false) bool isVerified,
  }) = _User;

  factory User.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) => _$UserFromJson(json);
}
```

### Freezed State Classes
```dart
@freezed
class WeatherState with _$WeatherState {
  const factory WeatherState.initial() = _Initial;
  const factory WeatherState.loading() = _Loading;
  const factory WeatherState.loaded({
    required WeatherData currentWeather,
    required Location location,
  }) = _Loaded;
  const factory WeatherState.error(String message) = _Error;
}
```

### Code Generation Commands
```bash
# Generate freezed files
dart run build_runner build

# Watch for changes
dart run build_runner watch

# Delete conflicting outputs
dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs
```

### Freezed Best Practices
- Always use `const factory` constructors
- Use `@Default()` for default values
- Implement `fromJson` and `toJson` when needed
- Use union types for state management
- Keep data classes immutable

## SPECIFIC IMPLEMENTATION NOTES

### Always implement these patterns:
1. Repository pattern for data access
2. Result/Either pattern for error handling
3. Dependency injection for services
4. Proper lifecycle management
5. Comprehensive error logging

### Never do these:
1. Hard-code API keys or sensitive data
2. Skip error handling in async operations
3. Ignore memory leaks (dispose properly)
4. Use print() for logging in production
5. Store sensitive data in SharedPreferences
6. Use Provider pattern instead of Riverpod
7. Create mutable state classes without Freezed
8. Skip code generation for data classes
9. Use setState() in complex state management
10. Ignore AsyncValue error handling

### Best Practices:
1. Use const constructors where possible
2. Implement proper null safety
3. Use meaningful widget keys
4. Handle device rotation and screen sizes
5. Implement proper accessibility features
6. Use Riverpod for all state management
7. Generate code with Freezed for data classes
8. Use AsyncValue for error handling
9. Implement clean architecture with features
10. Use go_router for navigation
11. Always run code generation after model changes
12. Use ref.watch() instead of Consumer when possible

This comprehensive rule set should guide Cursor to generate consistent, high-quality code that follows best practices for your WanderMood travel app. 